Youth Full Maine
September 8 at 12:44 PM ¬∑

We are resuming our curbside distributions this week in Old Orchard Beach and Saco, starting TOMORROW, WEDNESDAY: 9:15-10:00 a.m. OOB, behind the Loranger Middle School; and 11:30-12:30, at the Fairfield Elementary School in Saco. Please join us! Open to anyone from any town. Dayton and Biddeford's distributions will resume next week. All are in conjunction with new school hours. shared_text:
Youth Full Maine
August 26 at 12:17 PM ¬∑

At the beginning of the pandemic, we all learned about the millions of pounds of 2019 fall harvest potatoes in the U.S. that were going un-sold to restaurants and schools that had closed. There were news reports that most of it would have to be scrapped and buried. Thanks to the mobilization of all of our food partners and creative thinking, most of 2019's crop has been saved and shared with the broader community through programs like ours. We thank all of you for your patience with the bags of potatoes we have been distributing this spring and summer that have less than perfect contents at times (who knew how bad a rotting potato can smell??) and hope that you've been able to "edit" out the bad ones and still make delicious meals with the rest (boiling, broiling, baking, smashing, saut√©ing, frying...). The great news is that the majority of those potatoes have not gone to waste, and you all helped with that. And also, the fall 2020 potatoes will be harvested soon and made available fresh this September! Bon appetit!

shared_text:
City Government Biddeford Maine
July 15 at 3:29 PM ¬∑

The City of Biddeford is working with the USDA and the Episcopal Diocese of Maine in partnership with Pineland Farms to distribute 1,320 boxes of FREE food on Tuesday, July 21. The boxes will be available to any York County resident. The drive-thru distribution will take place at Biddeford Middle School, located at 25 Tiger Drive.

Food boxes will be handed out on a first come, first served basis beginning at 4:00 PM. Distribution will continue through 8:00 PM or while supplies last. Each box of food will contain Maine-made food products: 5 pounds of potatoes, 6 pounds of microwavable mashed potatoes, 2 ¬Ω pounds of cheddar cheese and a half-gallon of fresh 2% milk.

Message from Food & Nutrition Services Director, Caroline Trinder:

As you now know, school will be closed Monday, March 16. The current plan is for students to return on Tuesday.

IF school remains closed, we will be operating a meal program for ALL children 18 & under. Meals will be packaged to take home and will be picked up at Loranger Memorial School between 11:30am-12:30pm Monday‚Äôs-Friday‚Äôs for the entirety of any closure we may experience. Children will receive both a lunch for the current day and a breakfast for the next day.

Please rest assured we follow the highest level of hygiene and our goal is to make sure all of our community‚Äôs children do not need to worry about hunger amid everything else.

Please follow our page for any updates as we move forward through this process.

Meals will be packaged to take home and will be picked up at Loranger Memorial School between 11:30am-12:30pm Monday‚Äôs-Friday‚Äôs for the entirety of any closure we may experience. Children will receive both a lunch for the current day and a breakfast for the next day.

Please rest assured we follow the highest level of hygiene and our goal is to make sure all of our community‚Äôs children do not need to worry about hunger amid everything else.

Please follow our page for any updates as we move forward through this process.

post_text:
A note from our Food & Nutrition Service Director-

You may have heard about the romaine lettuce recall. We want to ensure we have time to take the right measures to obtain romaine from safe growing areas. Therefore, we will NOT be serving our entree salads this week only. We will use this time to work with our food vendors to obtain romaine from safe fields when we return from Thanksgiving Break.

After attending a produce training at the US Dept of Agriculture last year, I‚Äôm glad to know they have already determined the growing area affected by this E. Coli outbreak. As you may remember, last November it took weeks upon weeks to determine the source, putting all romaine farmers in America in true devastation.

Please take the time to check any romaine you may have in your house and toss any lettuce grown in the Salinas, CA region. All romaine will say on the packaging where it was grown. Romaine grown anywhere else is perfectly safe to eat. ü•¨

Happy Sunday,
Caroline

https://www.cdc.gov/ecoli/2019/o157h7-11-19/index.html

post_text: We're still working hard to bring the Fresh Fruit and Vegetable Program to Jameson Elementary School and Loranger Middle School starting October 1. This program is in addition to breakfast and lunch and is FREE for all students at these schools Tuesday- Thursday every single week. The logistics are still in the works, but this program was created to bring more fresh fruit and vegetables to our students, while introducing them to produce they may never have encountered. More to come, but we wanted to share the menu for October, as we think there are some pretty cool foods on there!
